segments.text: And to reach the end of Carl's tenure, the new building was being planned.
And what they were doing with that new building was primarily to make an activity building out of it.
They were going to give more space for program.
And me and a few others convinced them to change and make it a professional building, which would include the activity.
And that probably gave me some visibility in the department that I hadn't had before and also with Frank Hubert.
So when the time came to name the department head, Frank came over and said, OK, I need a question to ask.
Do you want to go outside or do you want to stay inside?
the faculty decided they wanted to stay inside.
Given that choice, faculty will always say that, or would then.
It may not be true now.
So he said, OK, then I'll take applicants, and we'll proceed.
And Linus and I were the only two who applied.
And Frank then set up a colloquium and each of us made a presentation.
To the department?
To the department and to the dean's staff.
And that was kind of a unique thing.
I'll never forget that day.
And Linus did a nice job with it.
But I believe by then Carl had already decided who, I mean, Dr. Hubert had already decided who he wanted.
But I may be wrong about that entirely.
What did you attempt to emphasize in your presentation?
Well, the deal was we couldn't talk about, we couldn't campaign for the job.
Yeah.
You know, the idea you present something academic.
And back then it was, I thought it was important
for the kinesiology or the physical education side of the house to understand what health was all about because we were a pretty poor second cousin at that point.
And so I spent my time primarily talking about what a health educator is and what he does and why.
And I don't recall what Linus said because I was second and I didn't hear a word he said.
because I was so focused on what I was thinking about.
About how long was your presentation?
Oh, about 30 minutes.
And was Dean present?
Dean was present.
Let's see, was McCandless with him?
No, he was already over in the provost's office then.
Hubert was there, Limbacher was there, Brian Cole was there, and Don Clark.
Those were the ones from the dean's office.
When you concluded your presentation, how did you feel you had done?
Pretty poorly.
Hubert was the only one to ask any questions, and he took issue with something I had said, and I have forgotten for the life of me what it is.
But it troubled me enough until I went home and wrote him a response and never sent it to him.
But I still have it.
How long did it take him to make the decision?
About three days.
And how did you learn what the decision was?
Good question.
I think Carl told me.
I think he relayed it through Carl.
I did get a letter later on.
But there wasn't a phone call or come over tomorrow?
No, I didn't go to him.
No, I didn't.
I found out the other way around.
In fact, I think the provost's office actually wrote the letter.
I'm not sure of that.
10 years ago, because I remember.
So this is 79.
That would be then among Hubert's, because he becomes, at about that time, he becomes the chancellor.
That's right.
He was an unusual person to work for.
I liked him a lot.
I was scared of him, but I liked him.
I'd had two or three opportunities to spend the day with him.
I think he arranged that on purpose.
We went over to Laga Vista for a day meeting that we had over there, and he insisted that I ride with him.
So I'm sure that he was trying to learn more about me.
The thing I remember most about him was that you really had to have your guns loaded when you went to see it.
Because he'd work you over if you didn't.
He just would hem you up and cone you.
And Carl had warned me about that.
I guess I may have been more afraid of him than I should have been simply because Carl had led me down that road.
But what I found was that if you really did your homework, you could convince him.
And if you ever convinced him,
you didn't have to worry about the rest of it.
He would make the argument on up the line.
And several nice things happened to us simply because I was ready for him those first few times.
But you didn't go over there and try out ideas with him.
You just couldn't do that because he would rip you if you didn't.
I can't say that I was sorry when he became chancellor.
because it did relax things a lot.
But we lost a lot at the same time because he was a very influential.
Influential is the right word, but he also was a very doggedly determined person to get things done.
Back as department head, you described the staff that you inherited at the dean's level.
I mean, the departmental level.
Oh, the departmental level?
Yeah.
It was... Was there a key secretary?
Oh, yeah.
As you know, every department had one.
Linda Stewart was outstanding.
How long had she been there?
She's been there one year longer than me, and I'm 29 years this year.
She had, well, not a year longer.
She's been at the university a year longer.
She was hired about a month before I was hired.
And of course, she just was outstanding.

Interesting thing about it, as Carl was getting older, he was 65 when he retired, and his memory was slipping, and Linda would use that because if she wanted to get something through, she'd say, you remember we talked about this the other day?
And he'd go, oh yeah, I remember that.
Well, when I came on, I was probably at the,
top of my game at that point, and she expressed many times she didn't like the fact that I was remembering things, but now I understand exactly what Carl was going through.
I can be tricked very easily.
Who else at the departmental level was there in the office?
At the time, we had a pool of secretaries in the front, and there was three of those girls, and then
The activity program had one or two.
And then Linda was my secretary.
Not long after becoming department head, I convinced Dean Hubert to let me name an assistant department head.
And that helped an awful lot.
Les Palmer was the person I chose for that.
What was the task of the assistant department head?
Primarily, he was the student academic advising person.
Back then, faculty advised students academically routinely.
And he helped faculty with those kinds of issues.
And also was the first line of visiting with students when they came in, undergraduate students.
As you think back, was that a good plan to have an academic advisor at the departmental level, a student advisor?
I think it was a good idea for faculty to advise students.
And I may have misled you.
I didn't mean that Les took over that job.
He coordinated the faculty.
I did think so because you needed someone to be the George Coonsey of that group of people because faculty were not real good at staying abreast of things that shouldn't be staying abreast of.
But I really thought we lost something when we went away from faculty advising students.
Now we have staff doing that.
And what happens is that

faculty build curriculum and we do all this argument and finally get consensus on what the curriculum is and then the academic advisor steers the student around the curriculum because their constituents are the students primarily, not the curriculum.
Like in the history department, Vic Treat, a long-time faculty member, when he retired they replaced him with a half-time TA.
Yeah.
Yeah.
And I mean, what does that TA know about advising?
That's right.
Undergrounders, no experience at all.
Did you inherit any particular problems when you became department head?
I inherited a swimming pool that I wish I could have filled up with concrete and made a roller skate rink or something out of it.
This was the old outdoor pool.
This was the old outdoor pool, and it had lots of problems.
It was like the old joke, you know what a boat is?
It's a hole in the water where you throw money.
That's what this was for us.
It was a hole where we put a lot of money.
Personnel, there were some problems.
There always is.
I called one faculty that was having difficulty coming to work and staying at work, and he tried me on because I was new.
And I'm sure I didn't handle it as well as Carl would have, but we got it handled.
Now, by that time, who were some of the good, solid old-timers that had retired?
Penberthy?
Penberthy was retired.
Actually, I came in at a unique time.
Penberthy retired, and we didn't have another retirement until Carl Landis.
And when he retired, he was the only retirement we had.
for another five, six, seven years.
So it was kind of a stable group.
And even though we had some old tried and true guys there, they were still a while off in retirement.
And the program at that point was healthy in number of majors and courses and so forth.
Good solid, solid cadre of students.
You're never satisfied with curriculum, obviously, and we still had some work to do there.
We began, as I look back, we began moving in the direction in physical education that we are now in that we're now more exercise physiology than we are physical education.
My goal when I was department head, I thought that the centerpiece of the program should be the teacher education program.
We were a college of education and that's what we ought to do.
And that exercise physiology ought to be a resource for those teachers.
Biomechanics should be, motor learning should be.
But you put two people together and suddenly they shake hands and become a specialty and then the world evolves around them.
And in exercise physiology, they were the brightest people we had.
They were well-prepared.
Many of them had degrees in physiology instead of physical education.
And what's happened is that those folks have actually become the department.
I don't know where that's going.
I hate to be an old, retired person who says the world is dissipating because I'm leaving.
It's not because I'm leaving, but I don't know where it's going.
I really don't.
Did any senior person like Carl Landis or Frank Huard, anyone else give you any advice as you became the department head?
Carl gave me a lot of advice, which I can't remember any particular things.
He told me where to sit in the dean's conference room.
He said, I always like to sit at the end of the table, because I can look dean eyeball to eyeball.
And that's what I did.
I did everything.
And it was useful, because I could tell facial expressions and body language.
He told me a lot of other things.
He worked me through one budget cycle, of course, and that helped an awful lot.

This is going to sound self-serving to you, and I want you to know I've told a lot of people this, but you were dean of faculties that year, and you established administrator's orientation, and it was the first time I believe that had been done.
And that was probably the single most important thing I did the first month of my job.
First of all, I met some people.
Bob Page is a good friend of mine still.
He was Dean of Engineering that year.
And I still have a good, close relationship with him.
But I learned, I thought I knew how the university operated,
But I learned things in that orientation that was unbelievable.
And I learned contacts and names that served me for the whole time I was there.
Now, that was my dream.
And I can't help but observe now, with the enrollment being considerably larger than it was then, how much more valuable such an effort would be today.
Sure.
What were your goals when you took over?
What did you hope?
you were going to leave the department to accomplish?
Yeah, I was hoping that we would build just the model I talked about, that we would develop a central program that all the specialties in our department would feed and build.
And I saw that happening in physical education and I saw it happening in health education.
For example, in health,
One of the things that health educators need is a good background in epidemiology.
Well, an epidemiologist is not a health educator, but you need that kind of person.
And so as they build, you go to them for their resources.
They didn't have to be in the department.
They could be someplace in the campus.
For their foundations and roots, they needed exercise, physiology, and those things.
Then the second thing I'd hoped to accomplish was to build a research program that could hold its own with the rest of the university.
A little while ago, you asked me had there been any relationships in the athletic department that was uncomfortable.
I was thinking a little while ago,
There was at least one that caused me lots of consternation.
You recall that, well, you weren't here to recall, but you read through the papers, I'm sure.
We hired Coach Sherrill to turn us around.
And his first year or two, he was not very successful.
And the Boo Birds were beginning to come out, as they want to do around here.
But finally, he did get it going.
And I don't remember.
It was his third or fourth year.
But he beat the University of Texas and won the Cotton Bowl.
I believe we beat Auburn in the Cotton Bowl.
And to reward him, the Board of Regents decided they wanted to give him tenure.
And I got a call from then President Frank Vandenberg.
And he says, Leonard, you know his deep voice and just really good one-on-one.
And I was in the faculty senate at that time.
I was deputy speaker.
And I'd had some interaction with him.
So we knew each other pretty well.
And I liked the old goat.
I mean, I better not say old goat, I guess.
He's a character in the biggest sense of that word.
I liked him a lot, and I think he liked me.
But he said, Leonard, the Board of Regents wants to reward Coach Sherrill for his winning year, and they'd like to give him tenure.
And of course, my first thought was give it to him in your department.
And I thought, oh my, what am I going to do now?
So I know I stumbled and I stuttered, but finally I said, you know, I just, I wouldn't think of doing this without consulting my faculty.
This is a faculty appointment.
This is a faculty decision.
And I need some time.
Oh, sure, sure, I understand that.
Take it through your process.
Well, that gave me some time to think about it a little bit.
And I called my

executive committee together and told him what was happening and I got some real good advice from them and some ways to approach it but they reaffirmed that there was no way that that should ever happen and if it did happen then that's just something we could not possibly stand for and so I called him back and the way I asked him was
or it's probably politically correct, but I'm not sure it was the best way of doing it.
I simply said that tenure and promotion was, again, a faculty decision.
We put these young people who are faculty through a lot of hoops to go through the tenure and promotion process.
Here's Coach Sherrill, doesn't even have a degree in our department.
His degree is in business.
And he certainly doesn't teach anything in our department.
He's done none of the things that we
that we require of our people to have to make tenure.
And we just don't really want to do that.
Now, let me assure you, Mr. President, that if in your wisdom, if you decree this, I don't think we're going to march on your office with banners and so forth.
But I just cannot do it.
Well, that's right, he said.
I think that's a good thing.
I may call the College of Business and talk with them.
I knew he was never going to do that.
But we dodged the bullet because a few days later, they did give him tenure.
And I've forgotten the title of what his tenure was.
Tenure of the university or tenure of something like that.
But it was a made-up title and was meaningless, of course.
And we dodged the bullet.
So you never heard any more about it?
I heard nothing more about it whatsoever.
And I think, I really think President Vandiver was embarrassed to call me.
I don't think he wanted to do that.
It was something he just was being a good soldier at that point.
But there was one other coach in the country that has tenure.
The guy Paterno at Penn State has tenure, I think, in the English department.
But he got that tenure about 40 years ago.
Other goals, go back to goals that you had as a department head.
I think I probably exhausted that.
Did you have some other schools out there that you wanted A&M to be ranked with in this field?
I probably lack vision, but that bothers me a little bit.
I think universities are making a mistake when they focus on being a top 10 school.
Not everybody can be the top 10.
There's only 10 that can be there.
And on what basis do you make that top 10?
And do you sell your soul and your heart when you do that?
And I'm really afraid that we have sold our heart to a large extent because we have faculty that don't care anything about students.
They don't care anything about their classes.
The only thing they care about is their discipline, and they don't care a lot about it in some cases, but it's their research projects because they know that's what's going to pay off.
And I'm of the opinion, and again, I'm an old goat that's about to retire, and that probably says something about me, but I'm of the opinion that
that the universities who are in the top 10 in the year 2020 are not going to look anything like the universities who are in the top 10 right now.
Because someone's going to discover that there's a goal, there's a responsibility that universities have.
And it's not to individual faculty members winning the Nobel Prize.
And I think we ought to, I hope we have a lot of them who do that.
But we're in the business of serving our constituents.
How did you encourage that attitude in the department?
It wasn't real hard to encourage because I think it was, in our department at that time, it was fairly common.
There were several faculty who didn't agree with that.
I really got blindsided in our department.
I always thought that if we were going to be hurt, we'd be hurt from the outside.
Someone criticizing us from the outside, and what happened was imploded.
We've changed from the inside almost completely.
I encouraged by simply preaching it and teaching it and trying to demonstrate it.
But I really thought everyone felt that way.
And it was right at the end of my tenure as department head when I realized that a cadre of folks weren't thinking that way at all.
And I also realized that that thinking was out of step with the rest of the university and the rest of the universities.
And that's when I knew it was time for me to step down.
You were department head for how long?
13 years.
From 79 to 80, whatever that is, 33.
What were your proudest moments during that time?
I think recruiting the first minority was a proud moment.
Our activity program was challenged in the faculty senate when we talked about the core curriculum and we were included as part of it.
That was a proud moment.
I was very pleased to be associated with the first chair in the College of Education, not only acquiring it, but in sitting in it.
In fact, the first two chairs was associated in our department.
I was, this is pretty small, but I was pleased with the way we handled the Jackie Sherrill tenure case, and I had a lot of help in that.
I was pleased to be able to hold factions together.
We had a very strong intramural program and we had a very strong exercise physiology program and a strong activity program and a strong professional program.
I held those together.
And they're beginning to unravel a little now.
Now intramurals is over in student services.
And I think that's a place for it to have been, for it to be.
It operates just as well and maybe better there.
But there are a lot of factions in our department now that I don't think existed then.
Now, as department head, what did you think was the appropriate decision-making pattern for you?
Were you the chairman bound by every majority vote, or were you to make the decisions without consulting with anybody, or what?
Somewhere in the middle of that.
I established what I called the DAC, the Department Advisory Committee, which included all the administrators, all the program leaders in the department.
And we met biweekly.
And I met opposite of where the college, the college met biweekly also, the college policy committee met biweekly also, and I met in opposite weeks.
I thought that faculty ought to be a part of every decision.
I always wanted to be a part of a decision.
If I opted out, then I would opt out, and faculty should be allowed to do that.
I also thought there were some things that faculty didn't want to make decisions about, and I should be willing to step forward.
And I thought there were some things that were too important
to be done by majority vote, but those were minimum.
I'm not sure I was a good department head.
I think it was a very enjoyable job for about six or seven years, a very difficult job for about four years.
Now, was I doing a better job those first six or seven or a better job at the end?
I suspect I was doing a better job at the end, but I was enjoying it more when it was early.
And during those years, what was your routine?
You got to the office about when and left about when?
I was there by 8, sometimes 7.30 every morning.
I hardly ever left before 7 in the evening.
And the first seven or eight years, I handled that very well.
The last four, that became really, really difficult.
Not the time, not the time I was in the office, but it was just the phone.
You've sat there, you understand.
When the phone rings, you jump because you know there's hardly ever anything good on the other end of that line.
Did any high-ranking board member, state politician, former student ever try to twist your arm during those years?
I don't think I recall a single time.
There was a period of time there where the board was
inclined to want to pick up the phone and talk directly to faculty and talk directly to department heads.
And I think it was during Vandiver's period of time where he requested that if that happened that we would notify the president's office immediately.
I don't think I ever had occasion to do that.
What did you do during those sometimes stressful
days and nights, what did you do for relaxation?
I stayed awake a lot, and I stomped my foot a lot.
I didn't exercise as much as I should have during that time.
I don't know the answer to that, you know, what you should do.
I know I didn't handle it real well.
You didn't play much golf.
You didn't take many trips.
I played some golf, and that's one thing I did do, but I didn't travel a lot.
I traveled some.
In the summertime, I got an opportunity to... All the department heads gathered in a national...
I got involved in that organization and really enjoyed that.
That was fun to get away.
But I didn't handle that well enough because my last year as department head, I was diagnosed with heart disease and had to have a four-way bypass.
I think stress had a lot to do with that.
During those 13 years, the number of degrees increased by about, did they double or?
in the department.
Degrees offered?
No, no, the degrees received.
Graduates.
Oh, yeah.
We doubled from...
From 72 to 84 we doubled, and then we leveled and stayed about the same after that.
Now our service activity picked up a lot, not just activity courses, but service courses that we taught in the department.
That picked up tremendously.
About how many new faculty members did you recruit?
Oh, in my time,
Gosh, I'd have to think on that a little bit, but just a rough guess, 15 or 20.
Oh, no, no, that's a tenure track faculty, hundreds of lecturers.
Yeah, yeah.
Now, who were those lecturers?
What did they do?
They taught the physical education activity courses.
Many of them were also working on their doctorates at the same time, but a large number of them were professional teachers who were going to work in that program forever.
That's what they did.
Describe working with Dean Corrigan, who came at about the same time you became a department head.
He was great.
He was great.
We had five candidates for that position, and he was my number four.
I've told him this, and so it's not a secret.
There was one guy I thought that was less suited for the job than him.

The reason I thought that, in all honesty, I liked him a lot, but the reason I thought that was he was at the University of Maryland, and at Maryland, health and physical education are in separate units.
They were not in the College of Education, and I just didn't think that he was going to understand what we were all about.
I couldn't have been more wrong.
There are a few things, errors that I made that was more wrong than that one.
He came on board, and we then,
Within six months of him taking that job, I suddenly realized one day sitting in his office that he knew more about my department than I did.
And what I didn't know was he'd been, well, I did know this, but I didn't realize that he had programs before.
His father-in-law was a basketball coach, so he knew sports.
He'd been a dean at Vermont, and he had physical education at that point, so he knew a lot more about the field than I thought he did, but he also was a good student.
The thing that probably impressed me the most, though,
was that we would sit around the policy committee table, and he would bring a problem to the table.
And we would start as department heads and associate deans and assistant deans to start talking about it.

And I recall looking at him and thinking, he's not interested in this, because he'd be sitting with his hand on his cheek and leaning like this, and sometimes it looked like his eyes would have glazed over.
And I recall one day looking at him and saying, he's about to go to sleep.

But then, in a moment, he'd stop the conversation, and he'd say, okay, here's what I heard you say, bam, bam, bam, bam, and he'd lay it off in three or four points, and here's the action I think we all take on the basis of what he thinks.
Most amazing group process person I've ever been associated with.

And where Dr. Hubert was the kind of person you had to be careful with and have your guns loaded, you could actually explore ideas with the card, and you could walk in there and say, you know, I just had a thought, and feel very comfortable with that.
maybe the best person I've worked for as a as an immediate supervisor.
And did he have a sense of humor?

Oh yeah funny funny guy funny guy and if you want to if if you want to ask him you know if you don't have much time to spend don't ask him a question because he'll talk with you as long as you'll you'll sit there.
I was the chairman of that search and that's you were I'd forgotten that one of the things I remember is that he was a dyed in the wool uh
football, baseball pro fan wondered could he adopt to the Astros and the Oilers.
That was one of his concerns.
Would he enjoy them?
He was a neat guy.
Under his leadership, did the department get fair treatment?
Oh, we got very fair treatment and the college moved.
I mean it really, now it didn't hurt to have a chancellor who was also from the College of Education.
Even though that's not a direct mix, it was nice to know that he was there.
We did a lot of good things.
One thing he brought in was his centers of inquiry.
And the idea was he wanted to cut across departmental lines.
And here was an issue somebody was interested in.
It doesn't matter if it was something in physical education or something in psychology.
If everybody was interested in it, then they would gravitate to that center.
A heck of a good idea, I thought.
